    {
      "id": "40d7007008f1dde6f7c605c2cc3ab865d67fced8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-24 08:05:53.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(10 inline comments)\n\nAs a general comment, while I think this is a very useful patch and I think we need to get this done, it will be some time before we can safely use any of the flags reclaimed by this patch, since older clients may set them sporadically and send them over the network.\n\nSome of them may in fact be completely unused in 1.8/2.x so could start to be used sooner.  It makes sense to document which flags are completely unused, and which ones will only become unused in 2.3 or 2.4 (depending where this patch lands) and cannot be used until we no longer require interoperability with those releases.\n\nAnother possibility is to send an \"OBD_CONNECT_LDLM_FLAGS\" flag for some time to indicate that the client/server have moved these internal flag values out of the wire flags, and they are safe to use.  At some point (e.g. 2.9.50) we could assume that the flags are \"clean\" regardless of whether OBD_CONNECT_LDLM_FLAGS is sent, but continue to send it for interop with older clients/servers, and by 3.4.50 just stop sending or masking OBD_CONNECT_LDLM_FLAGS entirely.  That schedule could be moved up if this patch gets into 2.1 and 2.3, and having the OBD_CONNECT_FLAG would avoid the need to check version numbers and allow porting this patch to any release.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "362c5caa822bf40cabc94631828e2be422bda5e6",
      "author": {
