    {
      "id": "12077db869f2165eeb021c9c4addd9cfe86ef23d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-12 04:01:34.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, approved\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nOne question that remains unanswered is when can we begin to start using these newly-liberated flags on the network?  Otherwise, the old clients/servers will be sending their internal flag values over the network, and confusing the peers that are expecting particular wire-value flags.\n\nOleg, what is your thought about also landing a patch like this for b2_3 and b2_1, maybe b2_2 also?  That would mean that we could start using these flag values around 2.5, if we assume that there is no longer interoperability requirements with 1.8.x after 2.4.x.\n\nPossibly a better solution is to define a new OBD_CONNECT_LDLM_FLAGS (0x4000000000000ULL) which signals that the client/server has applied this patch and is safe to use newer flag values.  Initially, nothing is requiring this feature, but it will help a great deal in the future when we DO need to use one of these flags for some reason.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "f363c21d3c9d1d23cba57eda87f42116c3bf5b32",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
        "email": "vitaly.fertman@hpe.com",
        "username": "vitaly_fertman"
      },
      "date": "2012-09-12 08:44:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)\n\n\"Otherwise, the old clients/servers will be sending their internal flag values over the network, \"\n\nactually, only non-wire flags get changed value, so no wrong flag will be sent over network. the issue is opposite, new client will send a new flag which will be considered as an old non-wire flag by old client, but will never be sent back over network by old client.\n\nI think each new flag could be considered separately when introduced. at that time a particular \"Used to be\" line is to be removed and this will play a role of reminder to check when this value was used last time and still is use somewhere.\n\nbesides that, such a new features which will send new flags over network usually get a new obd_connect flag, i.e. seems to be well protected.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
